# Feature Handoff Rule

When this included in the chat session, generate a SHORT project-level handoff summary.

The purpose is NOT to summarize the last feature in detail.

The purpose IS to:
- transfer overall current feature developing understanding
- preserve continuity
- preserve working patterns
- preserve architectural direction
- reduce context usage
- help a fresh agent onboard quickly

The handoff should stay relatively stable between sessions.

Most handoffs should be:
- mostly identical
- compact
- reusable
- focused on the overall project

Only a SMALL section should describe the most recent work.

---

# Handoff Structure

## 1. Feature Overview
Very short explanation of:
- what we are building
- main Feature goal
- overall direction

Keep this high-level and stable.

---

## 2. Technical Structure
Short summary of:
- stack
- architecture style
- important flows
- key folders/files
- important constraints

Only include things useful for fast onboarding.

---

## 3. Working Style / Collaboration Rules
Document how the user prefers to work.

Examples:
- prefers concise answers
- prefers simple solutions
- avoid overengineering
- preserve existing patterns
- mobile-first
- RTL support
- deterministic flows
- prefers incremental changes
- asks for Cursor-ready prompts
- etc.

This section is IMPORTANT because it preserves collaboration continuity between agents.

---

## 5. Recent Progress
Include only SHORT bullets for recent changes.

Example:
- added X flow
- simplified Y architecture
- refactored Z component
- integrated A into existing system

Keep each bullet extremely short.

Do NOT write long implementation history.

---

## 6. Open Items
Only important unresolved items:
- decisions
- uncertainties
- pending refactors
- architectural questions

Keep concise.

---

## 7. Quickstart
Very short onboarding instructions:
- files worth reading first
- commands if relevant
- areas to avoid touching initially

---

# Output Style

The output MUST be:
- compact
- stable between sessions
- high signal
- low noise
- optimized for AI consumption
- mostly bullets
- short sections
- minimal wording

Avoid:
- long explanations
- detailed feature history
- unnecessary implementation details
- repeating obvious information

The handoff should feel like:
“persistent project memory for a new agent”
—not—
“a detailed changelog of the last task”.

The ideal handoff is short enough to paste frequently without wasting context.